    "summary": "Re-sent profile updates and mini-retro (already provided)",
    "content": "Already sent both items in my previous messages:\n\n1. **Mini-retro**: Pipeline followed, commit atomic, suggestion to adopt the consensus tally the Driver maintains visibly. Sent two messages ago.\n\n2. **Profile updates**: 4 bullet points sent three messages ago. Here they are again for easy reference:\n\n- **Pre-implementation design discussion eliminates HTMX review blockers.** Steps 7, 8, and 9 all used design-before-code. In every case, zero HTMX-related blocking issues surfaced during code review. Getting the interaction pattern (which endpoint, what swap, what target) agreed before coding is faster than fixing it afterward.\n- **Extend existing endpoints rather than creating new ones.** For Step 9 (Clarify as Waiting For), using the existing `POST /inbox/{id}/clarify` endpoint with a new `clarify_type` radio value preserved progressive enhancement. A separate endpoint would have required JavaScript to dynamically rewrite the form action based on radio selection, breaking the no-JS fallback. When adding a new clarify path, add a branch -- not a route.\n- **Clearly distinguish blocking vs nice-to-have in review feedback.** The `<time>` element started as my nice-to-have but was later treated as blocking. This caused confusion. Always label feedback explicitly: BLOCKING, Minor, or Nice-to-have. If escalating a nice-to-have to blocking, state it explicitly with reasoning.\n- **Hypermedia patterns compound.** By Step 8, the dual-response pattern (HTMX -> fragment, non-HTMX -> redirect), announce triggers, focus management JS, and empty state toggling were all established templates. New features follow the pattern with near-zero design overhead. Consistency is its own reward.\n"
  }
}
